<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-476-591  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 476 591.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Sept 24 1990 n387 p3(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Channel DOS sales could boost profits: Microsoft skirts OEMs,turns to resellers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shore, Joel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microsoft Corp is adding MS-DOS 5.0 to the list of products itwill not sell through OEM agreements, but rather will controlitself through conventional reseller channels.andP;  Microsoft seems tohave learned a lesson from its troubles with the OEM marketing ofits SQL Server and LAN Manager products.andP;  Most computer resellersare pleased with the idea of selling the MS-DOS upgrade that willbe priced at $79.andP;  Analysts say Microsoft has found that it cannot rely on other firms to altruistically market its products forit.andP;  Observers say the move will enable Microsoft to squeeze morerevenue out of its products and will give it more control over themarket.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   MS-DOS 5.0 (Operating system) (marketing).andO;Topic:     Marketing StrategyOEMsDistribution AgreementsSoftware RetailingValue-Added Resellers.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>